<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> put oneself in someone’s place • take the place of someone</xh5><p> <i>put oneself in someone’s place</i>—(also: put oneself in someone’s shoes) imagine oneself to be in smb.’s position or predicament: Maybe I am overreacting, but <u>put yourself in my place</u>. How should I explain all this to my manager?</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>put someone in his place</b>—1. <i>scold a person, usually for rude remark or bad behavior:</i> He is being so mean to the customers. Someone needs to <u>put him in his place</u>! <i>2. remind smb. in an angry way that he is not as important as he thinks he is:</i> Somebody please <u>put him in his place</u>. As a scientist, I hate it when he speaks for “all scientists.”</p><p> <i>take the place of someone—</i>replace or supersede a person: Emile owed his education to an aunt, a saintly woman who <u>took the place of</u> his deceased mother.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> Neither expression correlates in meaning with the phrase <b>swap places with someone</b>—<i>exchange seats, jobs, etc. with another person: </i>In France last year there was an inmate who <u>swapped places with</u> his twin and escaped.</p> </entry>
